\begin_layout Proposition
Solovay tests are the same as Martin-Löf tests.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
Every Martin-Löf test is a Solovay test,
 so it suffices to show that every Solovay test induces a Martin-Löf test.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\{G_{n}\}_{n\in\N}$
\end_inset

 be a Solovay test.
 The main necessary lemma is the following:
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{n}$
\end_inset

 is the set of reals that are in at least 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 distinct 
\begin_inset Formula $G_{i}$
\end_inset

,
 then 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu U_{n}\leq\frac{\sum\mu G_{i}}{n}$
\end_inset

.
 This consists of applying Chebyshev's inequality on the function 
\begin_inset Formula $f(X)$
\end_inset

 given by 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

number of distinct 
\begin_inset Formula $G_{i}$
\end_inset

 containing 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

,
 whose integral is precisely 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum\mu G_{i}$
\end_inset

.
 Then,
 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{2^{n}}$
\end_inset

 is the associated Martin-Löf test.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proposition
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "prop:schnorrthm"

\end_inset

Let 
