 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $K(X\upto n)=K(\sigma_{2b_{0},k})\leq\abs{\sigma_{2b_{0},k}}-b_{0}+C=n-b_{0}+C$
\end_inset

.
 Setting 
\begin_inset Formula $b_{0}=b+C+1$
\end_inset

,
 we get:
 For any 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 there is 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $K(X\upto n)<n-b$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Proof
Finally,
 (a) implies (c):
 Suppose not (c).
 Then,
 there is some 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 such that,
