\begin_layout Proof
We build a prefix-free machine 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 as follows.
 On input 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

,
 first scan the input and give it to the universal prefix-free machine 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

.
 Keep track of the amount of input used by 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

,
 say 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau=\sigma x$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma$
\end_inset

 the input used.
 Next,
 scan 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

 until (if ever) you reach a length in 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

,
 say 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau=\sigma yz$
\end_inset

,
 with 
\begin_inset Formula $\length{\sigma y}\in R$
\end_inset

 and of minimal such size.
 Then,
 the output of our machine ought to be 
\begin_inset Formula $U(\sigma)y$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
This is clearly prefix-free,
 using the perspective that a prefix-free machine is one that scans its input without knowing its length and hangs if it tries to scan a part of the string that does not exist.
 We use it to provide a lower bound on 
\begin_inset Formula $K(X\upto n)$
\end_inset

 for arbitrary 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

.
 Indeed,
 fix such an 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

,
 and let 
\begin_inset Formula $r\geq n$
\end_inset

 be the smallest element of 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 above 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

.
 Then,
 
\begin_inset Formula $K(X\upto r)\geq r-b$
\end_inset

 by assumption,
 and moreover
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
K(X\upto n)+(r-n)\geq K_{M}(X\upto r)\geq K(x\upto r)-c\geq r-b-c,
\]

\end_inset

which can be rearranged to 
\begin_inset Formula $K(X\upto n)\geq n-b-c$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

,
 which implies that 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 is MLR.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
Okay,
 well.
 The idea seems to be along the lines of:
 if describing a prefix of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 is hard,
