\begin_layout Proposition
Define Chaitin's Halting Probability,
 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega$
\end_inset

,
 as the probability that some previously fixed universal prefix-free machine 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 halts on a randomly-generated input.
 Then,
 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega$
\end_inset

 is MLR.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
The fulcral idea is that 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega$
\end_inset

 could,
 if known,
 be used to calculate the Kolmogorov complexity of any given input string 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma$
\end_inset

.
 This could be done by approximating 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega$
\end_inset

 from below up to some close threshold 
\begin_inset Formula $2^{-n}$
\end_inset

,
 and after that point no description of size lower than 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 of any string could exist that hasn't already been found.
 We now put this idea into practice.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma$
\end_inset

 be a description of 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega\upto n$
\end_inset

.
 Then,
 this gives us an approximation of 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega$
\end_inset

 within tolerance 
\begin_inset Formula $2^{-n+1}$
\end_inset

.
 (Actually 
\begin_inset Formula $2^{-n}$
\end_inset

,
 but we haven't seen that 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega$
\end_inset

 is irrational yet.
 This will follow as a consequence of this proposition,
 of course.) By running inputs on 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 until we get to within this tolerance of 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega$
\end_inset

,
 we know that no new descriptions of size 
\begin_inset Formula $n-1$
\end_inset

 will ever be added.
 Thus,
 every Kolmogorov complexity up to (and including) 
\begin_inset Formula $n-1$
\end_inset

 are correctly found,
 and the remaining strings are exactly those that have complexity at least 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $F(\sigma)$
\end_inset

 be the (lexicographically,
 say) first string of complexity at least 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

,
 computed in this manner.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
In conclusion,
 we get a description for the first string of complexity at least 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

,
 using a constant term 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 (implement the code from the previous paragraph) plus a description of 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega\upto n$
\end_inset

.
 Thus,
 this string's complexity is at least 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 and at most 
\begin_inset Formula $b+K(\Omega\upto n)$
\end_inset

,
 and thus,
 for 
\emph on
every
\emph default
 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

,
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
K(\Omega\upto n)\geq n-b.
\]

\end_inset

Thus,
 (the binary expansion of) 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega$
\end_inset

 is MLR.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proposition
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "prop:omegajump"

\end_inset

The number 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega$
\end_inset

 is Turing equivalent to 
\begin_inset Formula $0'$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
Obviously 
\begin_inset Formula $0'\geq_{\turing}\Omega$
\end_inset

,
 because the Halting Problem can compute any left-c.e.
\begin_inset space \space{}
\end_inset

real.
 So,
 we focus on the other inequality.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
Suppose that we wish to know if a program 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

 terminates.
 Then,
 we can build a input for the universal prefix-free machine,
 which simply runs the program 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

,
 and halts iff 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

 does.
 This input will have some size 
\begin_inset Formula $f(P)$
\end_inset

,
 and knowing 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega$
\end_inset

 we can determine if 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

 halts by approximating 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega$
\end_inset

 within error less than 
\begin_inset Formula $2^{-f(P)}$
\end_inset

,
 and seeing if 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

 has halted by that point.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
This works for the specific prefix-free machine I have in mind,
 but let's try to come up with a proof that works for any optimal prefix-free machine.
 This means:
 We assume only that 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 satisfies that,
 for every prefix-free 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

,
 there is a constant 
\begin_inset Formula $d_{M}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $K_{U}(x)\leq K_{M}(x)+d_{M}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
Consider the prefix-free machine 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 which,
 on input 
\begin_inset Formula $0^{k}1$
\end_inset

,
 will check if 
\begin_inset Formula $k\in0'$
\end_inset

,
 and output the first string 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma\equiv\sigma(k)$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $K_{U}^{t}(\sigma(k))>k+1+d_{M}$
\end_inset

 if so,
 where 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 is the time it took for the 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

-th machine to halt.
 (We need some recursion theorem trickery to allow 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 to use 
\begin_inset Formula $d_{M}$
\end_inset

 in its own code.) Thus,
 here is our reduction procedure:
 To check if 
\begin_inset Formula $k\in0'$
\end_inset

,
 approximate 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega_{U}$
\end_inset

 until it is within 
\begin_inset Formula $2^{-k-d_{M}-1}$
\end_inset

 of the real value,
 and at that point run the program 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 for the amount of time taken until now,
 say 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

.
 We claim that,
 if the program 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 has not halted until now,
 it never will.
 This is because,
 if it did halt at some time 
\begin_inset Formula $t>s$
\end_inset

,
 we would have 
\begin_inset Formula $K_{U}^{s}(\sigma(k))\geq K_{U}^{t}(\sigma(k))>k+1+d_{M}$
\end_inset

,
 and yet 
\begin_inset Formula $k+1\geq K_{M}(\sigma(k))\geq K_{U}(\sigma(k))-d_{M}$
\end_inset

.
 Thus,
 
\begin_inset Formula $K_{U}(\sigma(k))<K_{U}^{s}(\sigma(k))$
\end_inset

,
 which means that 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega_{U}$
\end_inset

 will increase by at least 
\begin_inset Formula $2^{-K_{U}(\sigma(k))}$
\end_inset

 after time 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

,
 and since 
\begin_inset Formula $K_{U}(\sigma(k))\leq K_{M}(\sigma(k))+d_{M}\leq k+d_{M}+1$
\end_inset

,
 this means that 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega_{U}$
\end_inset

 will yet increase by at least 
\begin_inset Formula $2^{-k-d_{M}-1}$
\end_inset

,
 a contradiction.
\end_layout

