\begin_layout Section
Schnorr Randomness
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
A Schnorr test is a uniform sequence of computable opens 
\begin_inset Formula $\{U_{n}\}_{n\in\N}$
\end_inset

,
 whose measures are uniformly computable and satisfy 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu U_{n}\leq2^{-n}$
\end_inset

.
 A Schnorr random set is a set 
\begin_inset Formula $Z$
\end_inset

 that passes all Schnorr tests,
 i.e.
\begin_inset space \space{}
\end_inset

fails to be in almost all 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{n}$
\end_inset

 for every Schnorr test.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The restriction that the measures are uniformly computable distinguishes the Schnorr tests from the ML tests:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proposition

\strikeout on
If 
\begin_inset Formula $\{U_{n}\}_{n\in\N}$
\end_inset

 is a universal ML test,
 then 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu U_{n}$
\end_inset

 cannot be uniformly computable for cofinitely many 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof

\strikeout on
For each 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

,
 
\begin_inset Formula $2^{\omega}\setminus(\cup_{k>n}U_{k})$
\end_inset

 is a 
\begin_inset Formula $\Pi_{1}$
\end_inset

 class,
 and by measure estimation it cannot be empty.
 Thus,
 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu(\cup_{k>n}U_{k})$
\end_inset

 is MLR and hence noncomputable.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof

\strikeout on
Now,
 suppose that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu U_{n}$
\end_inset

 were computable for almost all 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

.
 Then,
 by inclusion-exclusion,
 and using the fact that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu U_{k}\leq2^{-k}$
\end_inset

,
 we can estimate 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu\cup_{k>n}U_{k}$
\end_inset

 to arbitrary precision.
 Indeed,
 the finite union 
\begin_inset Formula $\cup_{n<k\leq N}U_{k}$
\end_inset

 has the right measure up to a difference of 
\begin_inset Formula $2^{-N}$
\end_inset

,
 and so it suffices to show that (uniformly) if two effective open sets 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 have computable measure,
 so does 
\begin_inset Formula $A\cup B$
\end_inset

.
 To this effect,
 approximate the measures of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 to precision 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon$
\end_inset

.
 By that point,
 
\begin_inset Formula $A\cup B$
\end_inset

 will have the correct measure up to precision 
\begin_inset Formula $2\varepsilon$
\end_inset

,
 and we're done.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Remark

\strikeout on
We cannot extend this to 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $\mu U_{n}$
\end_inset

 is not computable for any 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

,
 because nothing stops us from adding empty sets,
 or clopen sets.
\end_layout

