\begin_layout Proof
If 
\begin_inset Formula $\{U_{n}\}_{n\in\N}$
\end_inset

 is a universal ML test,
 a set is MLR iff it fails to be in some 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{n}$
\end_inset

.
 As such,
 
\begin_inset Formula $2^{\omega}\setminus U_{n}$
\end_inset

 contains 
\emph on
only
\emph default
 MLR sets,
 and for 
\begin_inset Formula $n>0$
\end_inset

 has positive measure.
 Thus,
 
\begin_inset Formula $1-\mu U_{n}$
\end_inset

 is MLR,
 whence 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu U_{n}$
\end_inset

 is MLR itself.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
There was a nice recoverable thing,
 though.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proposition
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "prop:schnorrdescending"

\end_inset

If 
\begin_inset Formula $\{U_{n}\}_{n\in\N}$
\end_inset

 is a Schnorr test,
 then 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{n}=\cup_{k>n}U_{k}$
\end_inset

 is also a Schnorr test.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Lemma
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "lem:pi1classcomppositive"

\end_inset

Every 
\begin_inset Formula $\Pi_{1}$
\end_inset

 class of computable positive measure admits a computable member.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
The measure of a 
\begin_inset Formula $\Pi_{1}$
\end_inset

 class 
\begin_inset Formula $[T]$
\end_inset

 is always (and uniformly) approximable from above.
 Thus,
 if the measure of 
\begin_inset Formula $[T]$
\end_inset

 is computable,
 we can (uniformly) compute the measure of both branches,
 by approximating the measure of both branches until the sum of the approximations reaches the desired tolerance of the real value.
 As such,
 we can computably find a path in 
\begin_inset Formula $[T]$
\end_inset

 by repeatedly finding a branch of positive measure.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proposition
Every Schnorr test is passed by a computable set.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\{U_{n}\}_{n\in\N}$
\end_inset

 be a Schnorr test.
 We wish to find a computable set that fails to be in some 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{n}$
\end_inset

.
 To this effect,
 pick some 
\begin_inset Formula $n>0$
\end_inset

 and apply 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "lem:pi1classcomppositive"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $2^{\omega}\setminus U_{n}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We now show that we can slightly improve the type of Schnorr tests under consideration.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
First of all,
 by 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "prop:schnorrdescending"

\end_inset

,
 we can always turn Schnorr tests into descending Schnorr tests.
 More precisely:
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $Z$
\end_inset

 passes all Schnorr tests,
 then obviously it passes all descending Schnorr tests.
 On the other hand,
 if 
\begin_inset Formula $Z$
\end_inset

 passes all descending Schnorr tests,
 then it will pass an arbitrary Schnorr test 
\begin_inset Formula $\{U_{n}\}_{n\in\N}$
\end_inset

:
 Indeed,
 setting 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{n}$
\end_inset

 as in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "prop:schnorrdescending"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

,
 
\begin_inset Formula $Z$
\end_inset

 must pass this test,
 and hence will be in finitely many 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{k}$
\end_inset

,
 and in particular fails to be in some 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{n}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
On a similar note,
 we may assume without loss of generality that a Schnorr test satisfies that 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{n}$
\end_inset

 has measure 
\begin_inset Formula $2^{-n}$
\end_inset

.
 This is because,
 since the measure of 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{n}$
\end_inset

 is uniformly computable and less than or equal to 
\begin_inset Formula $2^{-n}$
\end_inset

,
 we can just add intervals to 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{n}$
\end_inset

 to pad it up to the correct measure.
 Similarly as above,
 this allows us to assume our tests satisfy this property.
 By being a little careful (only add intervals from previous padded 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{n}$
\end_inset

) and stacking with the previous paragraph,
 we can assume that our Schnorr tests are descending 
\emph on
and
\emph default
 have measure exactly 
\begin_inset Formula $2^{-n}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Also by 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "prop:schnorrdescending"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

,
 we may relax the condition on Schnorr tests to something Solovay-like.
 By default,
 if 
\begin_inset Formula $\{U_{n}\}_{n\in\N}$
\end_inset

