\begin_layout Proposition
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "prop:kucera1"

\end_inset

Let 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

 be a d.n.c.
\begin_inset space \space{}
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $0'$
\end_inset

-computable degree.
 Then,
 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

 computes a simple set.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
The classical idea behind creating simple sets is one of workers and requirements.
 For each 
\begin_inset Formula $e\in\N$
\end_inset

,
 we envision a requirement:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathllap{S_{e}\colon}\card{W_{e}}=\infty\rightarrow W_{e}\cap A\neq\emptyset.
\]

\end_inset

We will have a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

worker
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 looking out for each of these requirements.
 This worker,
 say worker 
\begin_inset Formula $e$
\end_inset

,
 will try to find an element of 
\begin_inset Formula $W_{e}$
\end_inset

 appropriate to add to 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

,
 under some restrictions,
 and once this element is added,
 worker 
\begin_inset Formula $e$
\end_inset

 will cease to act.
 This construction will ensure that 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 is c.e.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
One of these restrictions is that worker 
\begin_inset Formula $e$
\end_inset

 will only add an element 
\begin_inset Formula $x\geq2e$
\end_inset

.
 This,
 together with the assumption that each worker adds at most one element to 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

,
 ensures that 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 is coinfinite.
 It also implies that,
 to tell whether an element 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 is in 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

,
 it is only necessary to inspect the behavior of workers of index less than or equal to 
\begin_inset Formula $x/2$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
The other,
 and most important restriction,
 shall ensure that the behavior of worker 
\begin_inset Formula $e$
\end_inset

 is predictable to 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{s}$
\end_inset

 be a computable approximation of the 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

-computable d.n.c.
\begin_inset space \space{}
\end_inset

function 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

.
 As in the proof of the Arslanov completeness criterion,
 we consider defining a function by the recursion theorem as thus:
 
\begin_inset Formula $p(k)$
\end_inset

 is the program which computes 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{P_{k}}(p(k))$
\end_inset

.
 The fact that 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is d.n.c.
\begin_inset space \space{}
\end_inset

tells us,
 then,
 that if 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{k}$
\end_inset

 halts it must be to a time value before 
\begin_inset Formula $f(p(k))$
\end_inset

 has converged to its final value – and in fact to a time value at which 
\begin_inset Formula $f(p(k))$
\end_inset

 has a wrong value.
 However,
 in contrast to the c.e.
\begin_inset space \space{}
\end_inset

case,
 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

 is unable to calculate when this happens.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
Here is the restriction that we shall use:
 Worker 
\begin_inset Formula $e$
\end_inset

 is only allowed to add an element 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

,
 if the approximation of 
\begin_inset Formula $f(p(q(e)))$
\end_inset

 remains constant from 
\begin_inset Formula $t=x$
\end_inset

 to the time of addition (which is wlog greater than 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

),
 where 
\begin_inset Formula $q(e)$
\end_inset

 is the program that outputs the time it takes for worker 
\begin_inset Formula $e$
\end_inset

 to do this.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
Two verifications need to be performed.
 The first is that 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{e}$
\end_inset

 is,
 in fact,
 satisfied.
 The second is that 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

-computable.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
The first verification is easy enough:
 
\begin_inset Formula $p(q(e))$
\end_inset

 is a fixed program,
 whose approximation does converge after some 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{0}$
\end_inset

,
 so if 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{1}>x_{0}$
\end_inset

 is an element of 
\begin_inset Formula $W_{e}$
\end_inset

,
 it will eventually get added if no one else does.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
For the second verification,
 as we've observed before,
 it suffices for 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

 to be able to verify in finite time that worker 
\begin_inset Formula $e$
\end_inset

 will never add a certain number 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

.
 To this effect,
 suppose that it did,
 and that worker 
\begin_inset Formula $e$
\end_inset

 adds element 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 at some point.
 Then,
 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{q(e)}$
\end_inset

 converges to this time value,
 say 
\begin_inset Formula $t_{e}$
\end_inset

.
 Thus,
 it must be the case,
 by the discussion above,
 that 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{t_{e}}(p(q(e)))$
\end_inset

 is an incorrect approximation.
 Therefore,
 for 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 to be added by worker 
\begin_inset Formula $e$
\end_inset

,
 it must be the case that 
\begin_inset Formula $f(p(q(e)))$
\end_inset

 stays constant equal to this wrong approximation starting at time 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

,
 until 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 is added.
 Thus,
 we can simply query 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{x}(p(q(e)))$
\end_inset

.
 If this is correct (which 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

 can check),
 then 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 is not,
 in fact,
 added by worker 
\begin_inset Formula $e$
\end_inset

.
 If this is incorrect,
 then we wait until it changes.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 has not been added to 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 by that time,
 it never will.
\end_layout

