LatexCommand formatted
reference "prop:kucera1"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 to either of these.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Remark
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "prop:kucera1"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 implies,
 in particular,
 that no d.n.c.
\begin_inset space \space{}
\end_inset

degree below 
\begin_inset Formula $0'$
\end_inset

 is minimal.
 This can be strengthened:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proposition
No two d.n.c.
\begin_inset space \space{}
\end_inset

degrees below 
\begin_inset Formula $0'$
\end_inset

 form a minimal pair.
 More generally,
 one may find a simple set simultaneously below any finite number of d.n.c.
\begin_inset space \space{}
\end_inset

degrees below 
\begin_inset Formula $0'$
\end_inset

 simultaneously.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
The proof is the same as the proof of 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "prop:kucera1"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

,
 but we demand that the approximations of all the d.n.c.
\begin_inset space \space{}
\end_inset

functions remain constant.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "cor:fm1"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 proves that there is an incomplete noncomputable c.e.
\begin_inset space \space{}
\end_inset

set,
 but perhaps we instead want to build two incomparable c.e.
\begin_inset space \space{}
\end_inset

sets.
 Nies provides a way to do this (due to Kučera) using the recursion theorem and a uniform version of 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "prop:kucera1"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 to build two incomparable c.e.
\begin_inset space \space{}
\end_inset

sets.
 This uses the idea behind the cone-avoidance version of the Low Basis Theorem:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Theorem
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "thm:lowbasis"

\end_inset

Let 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

 be a nonempty 
\begin_inset Formula $\Pi_{1}$
\end_inset

 class,
 and 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 a non-computable set,
 there is a set 
\begin_inset Formula $Z\in P$
\end_inset

 that does not compute 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

,
 and such that 
\begin_inset Formula $Z'\leq0'\oplus B$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
Create a 
\begin_inset Formula $0'\oplus B$
\end_inset

-computable descending sequence of 
\begin_inset Formula $\Pi_{1}$
\end_inset

 classes.
 At stage 
\begin_inset Formula $e$
\end_inset

,
 filter for the conditions:
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Either 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{e}^{Z}$
\end_inset

 never halts,
 or it is guaranteed to,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
There is a (fixed) value of 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 for which 
\begin_inset Formula $\Phi_{e}^{Z}(x)\neq B(x)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Proof
Some proof is required to ensure the second bullet point.
 The idea is that,
 at any given step,
 we are working with a computable binary tree 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{n}$
\end_inset

 that represents the 
\begin_inset Formula $\Pi_{1}$
\end_inset

 class 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{n}$
\end_inset

.
 We can consider attempting to compute 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 by computing 
\begin_inset Formula $\Phi_{e}^{*}(x)$
\end_inset

,
 with the star meaning that we look through the nodes of 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{n}$
\end_inset

 to see if any of them furnishes an appropriate oracle.
 This cannot compute 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

,
 which means that there is some 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 for which 
\begin_inset Formula $\Phi_{e}^{*}(x)$
\end_inset

 either does not halt (which is good enough) or halts at an incorrect value for 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

.
 But this could correspond to a dead end for 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{n}$
\end_inset

...
 So,
 let's change tacks.
 Instead,
 we try to find a value of 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 for which one of the following two things happen:
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $\Phi_{e}^{Z}(x)$
\end_inset

 is guaranteed to never halt,
 or
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $\Phi_{e}^{Z}(x)$
\end_inset

 is guaranteed to halt to a value different from 
\begin_inset Formula $B(x)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Proof
The reason that this works is that,
 if it didn't,
 then by the first bullet point for every value of 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 we could look for a deep enough level at which 
\begin_inset Formula $\Phi_{e}^{*}(x)$
\end_inset

 is guaranteed to halt,
 even if potentially to multiple distinct values.
 But then,
 by the second bullet point,
 the wrong values are all dead ends,
 so we just try to prune the tree until a single stable value arises.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
More precisely,
 consider for every 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 the subtree of nodes on which 
\begin_inset Formula $\Phi_{e}^{Z}(x)$
\end_inset

 does not halt.
 If we find any 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 for which this is an infinite tree,
 cut down to that tree.
 Otherwise,
 we in parallel look for a value of 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 and a node 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma$
\end_inset

 with infinitely many children such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\Phi_{e}^{Z}(x)\iswd\neq B(x)$
\end_inset

.
 The argument from the previous paragraph shows that,
 assuming 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 noncomputable,
 one of these searches must eventually halt.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The idea behind Kučera's proof is to use a effective versions of 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "prop:kucera1"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "thm:lowbasis"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 and the recursion theorem as follows.
 Build a noncomputable d.n.c.
\begin_inset space \space{}
\end_inset

set 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

,
 from which you build a simple set 
\begin_inset Formula $X\leq A$
\end_inset

,
 and from 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 you build a noncomputable d.n.c.
\begin_inset space \space{}
\end_inset

set 
\begin_inset Formula $B\not\geq X$
\end_inset

,
 from which you build a simple set 
\begin_inset Formula $Y\leq B$
\end_inset

,
 and recursively we make it so that the original set 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 does not compute 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

.
 Then,
 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 cannot compute 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

 and vice-versa:
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $X\geq Y$
\end_inset

 then 
\begin_inset Formula $A\geq Y$
\end_inset

 which goes against our assumption.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To make this strategy work,
 we need to plug the following holes:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
We need to make 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "prop:kucera1"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 effective.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
We need to ensure that 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "thm:lowbasis"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 is effective.
 It already is!
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 is a 
\begin_inset Formula $0'$
\end_inset

-computable set given by a 
\begin_inset Formula $0'$
\end_inset

-index,
 the entire construction is effective in such an index.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
There is the issue that 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "thm:lowbasis"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 fails if given a computable set as input.
 In that scenario,
 the resulting 
\begin_inset Formula $0'$
\end_inset

-index is nontotal.
 We will fix this by effectivizing 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "thm:lowbasis"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 in a slightly better way,
 as to deal with the possibility of nontotal indices being given as input.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Nies proposes two distinct ways that 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "prop:kucera1"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 can be made effective,
 both of which boil down to discussing scenarios where we can effectively get an index for a d.n.c.
\begin_inset space \space{}
\end_inset

function.
 The first,
 and easiest,
 is the scenario where the given set 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

 is a 2-d.n.c.
\begin_inset space \space{}
\end_inset

function by itself,
 in which case there is not much to do in order to get a d.n.c.
\begin_inset space \space{}
\end_inset

function.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proposition
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "prop:kucera2"

\end_inset

There is a uniform procedure which,
 given a 
\begin_inset Formula $0'$
\end_inset

-index for a completion 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

 of the universal 2-valued function 
\begin_inset Formula $k\mapsto P_{k}^{2}$
\end_inset

,
 produces a c.e.
\begin_inset space \space{}
\end_inset

index for a simple set computed by 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The other is the scenario where the given set 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

 is MLR,
 in which case we can almost uniformly obtain a d.n.c.
\begin_inset space \space{}
\end_inset

function by taking 
\begin_inset Formula $n\mapsto Y\upto n$
\end_inset

.
 However,
 this function can fail to be d.n.c.
\begin_inset space \space{}
\end_inset

finitely many times.
 However,
 the proof of 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "prop:kucera1"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 goes through just fine,
 with the minor exception that the rule used to predict when Worker 
\begin_inset Formula $e$
\end_inset

 ceases to act is flawed.
 However,
 by hard-coding the errors into the reduction procedure,
 we still obtain:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proposition
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "prop:kucera3"

\end_inset

There is a uniform procedure which,
 given a 
\begin_inset Formula $0'$
\end_inset

-index for a MLR set 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

,
 produces a c.e.
\begin_inset space \space{}
\end_inset

index for a simple set computed by 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This version is weaker:
 While in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "prop:kucera2"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 we obtain a uniform index for the simple set 
\emph on
and
\emph default
 for the reduction procedure,
 in
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "prop:kucera3"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 the simple set is obtained uniformly but not the procedure.
 However,
 this does not matter for our purposes.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Remark
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "rmk:combinepi1class"

\end_inset

We shall combine either one of 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "prop:kucera2"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "prop:kucera3"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 with the fact that there exists a nonempty 
\begin_inset Formula $\Pi_{1}$
\end_inset

 class all of whose elements are completions of the universal 2-valued function or MLR sets,
 respectively.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Unfortunately,
 effectivizing 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "thm:lowbasis"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 in an appropriate way seems to be difficult,
 because the specific thing that needs to be done is pretty specific to the current situation.
 So we'll just skip to the proof:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proposition
There exists a pair of incomparable c.e.
\begin_inset space \space{}
\end_inset

sets.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
Build 
\begin_inset Formula $0'$
\end_inset

-indices 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

,
 ostensibly of some appropriate 
\begin_inset Formula $\Pi_{1}$
\end_inset

 class as per 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "rmk:combinepi1class"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

,
 by the recursion theorem as follows.
 From 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

,
 build a c.e.
\begin_inset space \space{}
\end_inset

set 
\begin_inset Formula $X=W_{x}$
\end_inset

 per 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "prop:kucera1"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $A=\{a\}^{0'}$
\end_inset

 is total and noncomputable,
 then 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 is noncomputable.
 Now,
 apply a modified effective version of 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "thm:lowbasis"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 to build 
\begin_inset Formula $B=\{b\}^{0'}\not\geq X$
\end_inset

 as such:
 In parallel with the search for the next 
\begin_inset Formula $\Pi_{1}$
\end_inset

 subclass,
 prune the 
\begin_inset Formula $\Pi_{1}$
\end_inset

 class corresponding to 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

.
 Likewise,
 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 will be obtained by applying this same construction,
 and when the construction is waiting on the next subclass,
 prune 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

.
 Anyway,
 then from 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 build a c.e.
\begin_inset space \space{}
\end_inset

set 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

,
 and build 
\begin_inset Formula $A\not\geq Y$
\end_inset

 in this manner.
 (Note:
 The inequalities 
\begin_inset Formula $B\not\geq X$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $A\not\geq Y$
\end_inset

 are only guaranteed to hold if the opposite construction does not hang.
 Thus,
 
\begin_inset Formula $B\not\geq X$
\end_inset

 is only guaranteed if 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

 is noncomputable.)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
This construction ensures that at most one of 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 is nontotal – because every time spent hanging on one is spent adding more bits to the other.
 Thus,
 suppose that 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 is total.
 Then,
 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 is noncomputable,
 which ensures that 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 is total,
 which ensures that 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

 is noncomputable.
 As such,
 all (non-)inequalities we need are guaranteed to hold:
 
\begin_inset Formula $A\not\geq Y$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $A\geq X$
\end_inset

,
 so 
\begin_inset Formula $X\not\geq Y$
\end_inset

 and vice-versa.
 This completes the proof.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
D.n.c.
\begin_inset space \space{}
\end_inset

Shenanigans
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Being PA is a strengthening of being d.n.c.
 But it's a rather strong strengthening.
 We will see shortly that,
 while almost every set is d.n.c.
\begin_inset space \space{}
\end_inset

(because almost every set is MLR),
 almost no set is PA.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proposition
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $Z$
\end_inset

 be a MLR set.
 Then,
 
\begin_inset Formula $Z$
\end_inset

 is PA iff 
\begin_inset Formula $Z\geq0'$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
(
\begin_inset Formula $\leftarrow$
\end_inset

) is obvious,
 so we prove (
\begin_inset Formula $\rightarrow$
\end_inset

).
 In other words,
 let 
\begin_inset Formula $Z$
\end_inset

 be a MLR set that computes a completion of the universal 
\begin_inset Formula $2$
\end_inset

-valued function,
 say via 
\begin_inset Formula $\Gamma^{Z}$
\end_inset

.
 We will show that 
\begin_inset Formula $Z$
\end_inset

 dominates an arbitrary partial computable function 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
We build an appropriate ML test as follows.
 The set 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{n}$
\end_inset

 behaves as thus.
 By the recursion theorem,
 define 
\begin_inset Formula $2$
\end_inset

-valued programs 
\begin_inset Formula $e_{1},\dots,e_{n}$
\end_inset

 as follows.
 Look in the binary tree of all possibilities,
 for 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi(n)$
\end_inset

 time,
 to approximate the measure of the sets whose output of 
\begin_inset Formula $\Gamma^{X}(\vec{e})=(\Gamma^{X}(e_{1}),\dots,\Gamma^{X}(e_{n}))$
\end_inset

 is each possible value.
 Since there are 
\begin_inset Formula $2^{n}$
\end_inset

 possible vector outputs,
 and the sets of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 each of these correspond to are distinct,
 one of these possibilities must be less than 
\begin_inset Formula $2^{-n}$
\end_inset

 in measure,
 and so one of our 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi(n)$
\end_inset

-time approximations must be less than 
\begin_inset Formula $2^{-n}$
\end_inset

.
 We set 
\begin_inset Formula $e_{1},\dots,e_{n}$
\end_inset

 to be programs whose output minimizes this approximate measure,
 and set 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{n}$
\end_inset

 to be the collection of sets 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 which,
 by time 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi(n)$
\end_inset

,
 will have satisfied 
\begin_inset Formula $\Gamma^{X}(\vec{e})=P_{\vec{e}}$
\end_inset

,
 and so in in particular 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu U_{n}\leq2^{-n}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
Now,
 since 
\begin_inset Formula $Z$
\end_inset

 is MLR,
 it must fail the ML test given by 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{n}$
\end_inset

.
 By Solovay shenanigans,
 this implies that,
 for all large enough 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

,
 
\begin_inset Formula $Z$
\end_inset

 is not in 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{n}$
\end_inset

.
 We show that,
 for such values of 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

,
 if 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi(n)\iswd$
\end_inset

 then a certain 
\begin_inset Formula $Z$
\end_inset

-computable expression must majorize 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi(n)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
So...
 Suppose that 
\begin_inset Formula $Z$
\end_inset

 is not in 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{n}$
\end_inset

,
 and that 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi(n)\iswd$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\Gamma^{Z}(\vec{e})=P_{\vec{e}}$
\end_inset

,
 for 
\begin_inset Formula $Z$
\end_inset

 not to be in 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{n}$
\end_inset

,
 the time by which 
\begin_inset Formula $\Gamma^{Z}(\vec{e})$
\end_inset

 will have been found to equal 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{e}$
\end_inset

 must be greater than 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi(n)$
\end_inset

.
 So...
 That's it,
 that's the expression:
 The dominant function is 
\begin_inset Formula $f(n)$
\end_inset

 given by:
 Time it takes an exhaustive search for nodes satisfying 
\begin_inset Formula $\Gamma^{\sigma}(\vec{e})=\Gamma^{Z}(\vec{e})$
\end_inset

 to find a prefix of 
\begin_inset Formula $Z$
\end_inset

.
 (We use 
\begin_inset Formula $\Gamma^{Z}(\vec{e})$
\end_inset

 because 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{\vec{e}}$
\end_inset

 does not always terminate.)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Corollary
Almost no set is PA.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
The collection of PA sets is contained in the collection of sets that are not MLR,
 together with the collection of sets that compute 
\begin_inset Formula $0'$
\end_inset

.
 In particular,
 it is contained in the collection of sets that are not 
\begin_inset Formula $2$
\end_inset

-random.
 That collection has measure 1,
 and thus the PA sets are contained in a set of measure zero.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
We could also have used 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "prop:setsabovemeasurezero"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 to conclude that this collection has measure zero.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Exercise
Show that for each low set 
\begin_inset Formula $Z$
\end_inset

 there is a simple set 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $Z\oplus A$
\end_inset

 is low.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
First,
 we find a d.n.c.
\begin_inset space \space{}
\end_inset

set 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $Z\oplus B$
\end_inset

 is low.
 Then,
 we apply 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "prop:kucera1"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 to obtain a simple set below 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

,
 which then satisfies the required property.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
We claim that 
\begin_inset Formula $B=\Omega_{0}^{Z}$
\end_inset

 does what we want.
 To this effect,
 we shall apply 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "prop:g1mlr2"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 as follows.
 We know that 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega^{Z}$
\end_inset

 is MLR rel 
\begin_inset Formula $Z$
\end_inset

.
 Thus,
 by van
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Lambalgen,
 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega_{1}^{Z}$
\end_inset

 is MLR rel 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega_{0}^{Z}\oplus Z$
\end_inset

.
 Moreover,
 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega_{1}^{Z}$
\end_inset

 is computable in 
\begin_inset Formula $Z'\equiv0'$
\end_inset

.
 Thus,
 we conclude 
\begin_inset Formula $(\Omega_{0}^{Z}\oplus Z)'\equiv\Omega_{0}^{Z}\oplus Z\oplus0'\equiv0'$
\end_inset

,
 which concludes the proof.
